concept_explanation.iterating_string:
To iterate characters of a String, you can't use for-each directly. Use `charAt` with index:

```java
String s = "Hello";
for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
    char c = s.charAt(i);
    System.out.println(c);
}
```

Prints `H, e, l, l, o` on separate lines.

**Alternative**: convert to char array first

```java
String s = "Hello";
char[] chars = s.toCharArray();
for (char c : chars) {
    System.out.println(c);
}
```

Both approaches work. `charAt` is more direct; `toCharArray` allows for-each.

concept_explanation.string_pool_brief:
**Brief mention** (full coverage in OOP module):

Java maintains a **String Pool** — a special area of memory where String literals are stored. Identical literals point to the same object.

```java
String a = "hello";
String b = "hello";
// Both point to the SAME object in the string pool

String c = new String("hello");
// Forces a NEW object outside the pool
```

This is why `a == b` is often true for literals (same object) but is NOT something to rely on. The interning optimization is real but unpredictable.

**Bottom line**: still use `.equals()` for comparison. The pool is an implementation detail you shouldn't depend on.

step_by_step_solution.details:
Cleaning input is step 1 of every input validation:

```java
public static String normalize(String email) {
    if (email == null) return "";
    return email.trim().toLowerCase();
}
```

**Notice**:
- Null check: defensive. Many APIs return null for missing data.
- `.trim()` removes leading/trailing whitespace (`"  aisha@example.com  "` → `"aisha@example.com"`)
- `.toLowerCase()` standardizes case (`"AISHA@example.com"` → `"aisha@example.com"`)
- We CHAIN method calls: `.trim().toLowerCase()` works because each method returns a new String we can call methods on.
- Returns a NEW String (original unchanged — strings are immutable).

Check structure with String methods:

```java
public static boolean isValidFormat(String email) {
    String e = normalize(email);

    if (e.isEmpty()) return false;

    // Must have exactly one @
    int atIndex = e.indexOf('@');
    if (atIndex == -1) return false;  // no @
    if (e.indexOf('@', atIndex + 1) != -1) return false;  // multiple @

    // Local part (before @)
    String local = e.substring(0, atIndex);
    if (local.isEmpty()) return false;
    if (local.contains(" ")) return false;

    // Domain part (after @)
    String domain = e.substring(atIndex + 1);
    if (domain.isEmpty()) return false;
    if (!domain.contains(".")) return false;
    if (domain.contains(" ")) return false;

    return true;
}
```

**Notice the multiple String methods**:
- `.isEmpty()` — checks for empty string
- `.indexOf('@')` — finds @ position, -1 if missing
- `.indexOf('@', atIndex + 1)` — searches for second @
- `.substring(0, atIndex)` — extracts local part
- `.substring(atIndex + 1)` — extracts domain (from atIndex+1 to end)
- `.contains(" ")` — checks for spaces
- `.contains(".")` — checks for the required dot in domain

Each check is one early return — easy to read, easy to add new checks.

Just extract the part after @:

```java
public static String getDomain(String email) {
    String e = normalize(email);
    int atIndex = e.indexOf('@');
    if (atIndex == -1) return "";
    return e.substring(atIndex + 1);
}
```

For `"aisha@gmail.com"` → returns `"gmail.com"`.

Notice we call `normalize` first — consistency with isValidFormat. Caller's email is unchanged (immutability).

Test cases covering valid emails, edge cases, and invalid ones:

```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
    String[] testEmails = {
        "aisha@gmail.com",
        "RAJ.PATEL@hdfc.co.in",
        "  vikram@example.com  ",
        "not-an-email",
        "@nodomain.com",
        "nolocal@",
        "two@@signs.com",
        "spaces in@local.com",
        "missing-dot@domain",
        ""
    };

    for (String email : testEmails) {
        boolean valid = isValidFormat(email);
        String domain = getDomain(email);
        String normalized = normalize(email);

        System.out.println("'" + email + "' → valid: " + valid 
            + ", domain: '" + domain + "', normalized: '" + normalized + "'");
    }
}
```

Notice we use single quotes (within strings) around values for clarity in output.

worked_example.final_code:
public class EmailValidator {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String[] testEmails = {
            "aisha@gmail.com",
            "RAJ.PATEL@hdfc.co.in",
            "  vikram@example.com  ",
            "not-an-email",
            "@nodomain.com",
            "nolocal@",
            "two@@signs.com",
            "spaces in@local.com",
            "missing-dot@domain",
            ""
        };

        for (String email : testEmails) {
            boolean valid = isValidFormat(email);
            String domain = getDomain(email);
            String normalized = normalize(email);

            System.out.println("'" + email + "' → valid: " + valid 
                + ", domain: '" + domain + "', normalized: '" + normalized + "'");
        }
    }

    public static String normalize(String email) {
        if (email == null) return "";
        return email.trim().toLowerCase();
    }

    public static boolean isValidFormat(String email) {
        String e = normalize(email);

        if (e.isEmpty()) return false;

        int atIndex = e.indexOf('@');
        if (atIndex == -1) return false;
        if (e.indexOf('@', atIndex + 1) != -1) return false;

        String local = e.substring(0, atIndex);
        if (local.isEmpty()) return false;
        if (local.contains(" ")) return false;

        String domain = e.substring(atIndex + 1);
        if (domain.isEmpty()) return false;
        if (!domain.contains(".")) return false;
        if (domain.contains(" ")) return false;

        return true;
    }

    public static String getDomain(String email) {
        String e = normalize(email);
        int atIndex = e.indexOf('@');
        if (atIndex == -1) return "";
        return e.substring(atIndex + 1);
    }
}

